authentication, sensitive data exposure","Insecure deserialization, XXE, broken access control","Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) and Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","Live attack demonstrations and in-code mitigations"]},{title:"3. Secure Coding: Input Validation, Output Encoding, Error Handling",points:["Validating input at every layer (client, server, database)","Output encoding to prevent XSS and injection attacks","Error handling that does not leak stack traces or internal data","Defensive programming: assume all input is hostile"]},{title:"4. Authentication, Authorization & Session Management",points:["Proper password hashing implementation (bcrypt, Argon2)","JWT, OAuth 2.0, and secure session management","Multi-factor authentication (MFA) in your application","Role-based access control (RBAC) and principle of least privilege"]},{title:"5. Data Security: Encryption, Hashing, Secret Management",points:["Encryption vs hashing vs encoding \u2014 when to use which","Secure secret storage (Vault, AWS Secrets Manager, .env)","Never commit secrets to Git \u2014 and how to clean up history when you do","TLS, HTTPS, and encryption at-rest vs in-transit"]},{title:"6. API Security & Supply Chain (Dependency Risk)",points:["Rate limiting, API key rotation, API gateways","Risks in npm/pip/composer dependencies and how to audit them","Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) and dependency scanning","Log4shell and event-stream case studies \u2014 early detection patterns"]},{title:"7. Safe AI: Using ChatGPT/Claude/Copilot Securely",points:["What you must NEVER paste into a public AI prompt","Prompt injection risks in your own LLM-powered applications","Self-hosted vs commercial API \u2014 data security trade-offs","Building a sensible AI policy for engineering teams"]},{title:"8. AI for Security: Code Review, Static Analysis, Threat Detection",points:["Using AI for automated code review and vulnerability detection","AI-assisted Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","Anomaly detection in production logs using AI models","Practical workflow: PR review + CI/CD + AI security gate"]},{title:"9. Incident Response, Logging & Audit Trails",points:["What counts as a security incident and how to classify it","Useful logging vs logging that leaks sensitive data","Incident response plan: who, when, and how to report","72-hour breach notification obligation under UU PDP and GDPR"]},{title:"10. Certification Exam",points:["10\u201320 multiple-choice questions covering all course material","Minimum passing score: 80%","Official certificate issued to participants who pass"]}],v=[{question:"You receive a username input and place it directly into a SQL query. What is the biggest risk?",options:["Nothing \u2014 as long as the input is validated on the frontend","SQL Injection \u2014 an attacker can run arbitrary database queries","Only a performance problem, not a security one","Just escape spaces and you're safe"],correct:1},{question:"Your team wants to use Copilot to speed up coding. Which is the safest practice?",options:["Paste the entire codebase into the prompt so the AI has full context","Include API keys in comments to get more accurate suggestions","Never paste secrets, customer data, or confidential code into public AI prompts","Disable AI for the whole team \u2014 there is no safe way to use it"],correct:2},{question:"You accidentally commit a .env file containing the production database password to a public GitHub repository. What is the correct first step?",options:["Just remove the file from the latest commit \u2014 the password is still safe","Treat the credentials as compromised \u2014 rotate all secrets immediately, then clean the Git history","Make the repo private \u2014 nobody will find it","Wait until someone reports it"],correct:1},{question:"To store user passwords in your database, which method is correct?",options:["Store them in plain text for easier debugging","Encrypt them with AES using a key stored in the source code","Hash them with bcrypt or Argon2 using a unique salt per user","Encode them with base64 \u2014 that is secure enough"],correct:2},{question:"An npm library you depend on announces a critical RCE vulnerability. What is the first step?",options:["Wait for the next major version of the library","Remove all npm dependencies from the project","Check whether your app is affected, then update to the patched version immediately","Don't worry \u2014 npm vulnerabilities are rarely exploited"],correct:2}];function j(){var e=(0,l.useState)({}),t=e[0],r=e[1],a=(0,l.useState)(!1),i=a[0],s=a[1],o=i?v.reduce((function(e,r,n){return e+(t[n]===r.correct?1:0)}),0):0;return(0,p.jsxs)("div",{children:[(0,p.jsx)("div",{className:"space-y-8",children:v.map((function(e,a){return(0,p.jsxs)("div",{className:"bg-gray-800 rounded-lg p-6 border border-gray-700",children:[(0,p.jsxs)("p",{className:"text-white font-semibold mb-4",children:[a+1,". ",e.question]}),(0,p.jsx)("div",{className:"space-y-3",children:e.options.map((function(s,o){var l="border-gray-600",c="bg-gray-800";return i?o===e.correct?(l="border-green-500",c="bg-green-500/10"):t[a]===o&&o!==e.correct&&(l="border-red-500",c="bg-red-500/10"):t[a]===o&&(l="border-prime-100",c="bg-prime-100/10"),(0,p.jsxs)("button",{onClick:function(){return e=a,t=o,void(i||r((function(r){return h(h({},r),{},(0,n.Z)({},e,t))})));var e,t},className:"w-full text-left p-4 rounded-lg border ".concat(l," ").concat(c," text-gray-300 hover:border-prime-100 transition-colors ").concat(i?"cursor-default":"cursor-pointer"),children:[(0,p.jsxs)("span",{className:"font-semibold text-gray-400 mr-3",children:[String.fromCharCode(65+o),"."]}),s]},o)}))})]},a)}))}),(0,p.jsx)("div",{className:"mt-8 text-center",children:i?(0,p.jsxs)("div",{className:"bg-gray-800 rounded-xl p-8 border border-gray-700",children:[(0,p.jsxs)("p",{className:"text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-2",children:[o," / ",v.length]}),(0,p.jsx)("p",{className:"text-gray-400 text-lg",children:o===v.length?"Perfe